From: Bob Van Valzah <bob@vanvalzah.com>
Subject: [PATCH] igc: serialize TIMINCA write with pending TX timestamps

igc_ptp_adjfine_i225() writes IGC_TIMINCA without any synchronization.
When ptp4l (or any PTP stack) sends hardware-timestamped packets while
a clock discipline daemon adjusts the frequency, the TIMINCA change can
race with the hardware's TX timestamp capture, producing a corrupt
timestamp that the driver interprets as "not ready."  After
IGC_PTP_TX_TIMEOUT (15s), the driver logs "Tx timestamp timeout" and
eventually the EXTTS subsystem stops delivering PPS events.

This is easily reproducible: one thread calling clock_adjtime
(ADJ_FREQUENCY) at ~200k/s while another sends hardware-timestamped
UDP packets at ~100k/s triggers the timeout within 17 seconds.  At
realistic rates (1 adjfine/s + 128 sync/s), the race takes ~30 minutes
to trigger.

Every other PTP clock operation in igc_ptp.c (adjtime, gettime, settime)
holds tmreg_lock, but adjfine does not.  However, the race is between
TIMINCA and the TX timestamp capture hardware, not between software
register accesses.  Adding tmreg_lock alone does not fix it.

Fix: hold ptp_tx_lock around the TIMINCA write and skip the write if
any TX timestamps are pending (tx_tstamp[i].skb != NULL).  This
prevents the hardware from seeing a rate change while a timestamp is
in flight.  Return -EBUSY so the PTP subsystem can retry.

Under stress testing, this extends the time-to-failure from 17s to 43s.
At realistic rates (1 Hz discipline + 128 Hz PTP sync), the residual
race probability gives an estimated MTBF of ~25 years.

Signed-off-by: Bob Van Valzah <bob@vanvalzah.com>
---
 drivers/net/ethernet/intel/igc/igc_ptp.c | 18 +++++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 17 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/igc/igc_ptp.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/igc/igc_ptp.c
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/igc/igc_ptp.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/intel/igc/igc_ptp.c
@@ -47,8 +47,10 @@ static int igc_ptp_adjfine_i225(struct ptp_clock_info *ptp, long scaled_ppm)
 {
 	struct igc_adapter *igc = container_of(ptp, struct igc_adapter,
 					       ptp_caps);
 	struct igc_hw *hw = &igc->hw;
+	unsigned long flags;
 	int neg_adj = 0;
 	u64 rate;
 	u32 inca;
+	int i;

 	if (scaled_ppm < 0) {
 		neg_adj = 1;
@@ -63,7 +65,21 @@ static int igc_ptp_adjfine_i225(struct ptp_clock_info *ptp, long scaled_ppm)
 	if (neg_adj)
 		inca |= ISGN;

-	wr32(IGC_TIMINCA, inca);
+	/* Changing the clock increment rate while a TX timestamp is being
+	 * captured by the hardware can corrupt the timestamp, causing the
+	 * driver to report "Tx timestamp timeout" and eventually wedging
+	 * the EXTTS subsystem.  Serialize with pending TX timestamps:
+	 * skip the rate change if any are in flight.
+	 */
+	spin_lock_irqsave(&igc->ptp_tx_lock, flags);
+	for (i = 0; i < IGC_MAX_TX_TSTAMP_REGS; i++) {
+		if (igc->tx_tstamp[i].skb) {
+			spin_unlock_irqrestore(&igc->ptp_tx_lock, flags);
+			return -EBUSY;
+		}
+	}
+	wr32(IGC_TIMINCA, inca);
+	spin_unlock_irqrestore(&igc->ptp_tx_lock, flags);

 	return 0;
 }
